04:04.495 --> 04:06.451
She was crying. She's scared, Mr. Batiste.

04:07.748 --> 04:08.828
Okay.

04:10.668 --> 04:14.832
Okay, let's start class.
You kids take your places, hear?

04:17.216 --> 04:18.456
Come on.

04:22.805 --> 04:24.045
You, too, girl.

04:39.780 --> 04:41.645
ALBERT: The Seb'm Ward.

04:41.740 --> 04:43.947
Nobody said "Seventh."

04:44.869 --> 04:47.702
Some called it Creoleville.

04:47.788 --> 04:50.165
But it was whites here and blacks, too.

04:50.249 --> 04:53.036
Folks with Choctaw Indian in them.

04:53.127 --> 04:56.119
French blood as well.

04:56.213 --> 04:57.168
High yellows.

04:57.256 --> 05:00.544
-This was before integration?
-Yeah.

05:00.634 --> 05:03.626
Before things blew up
and got pretty ugly in the '60s.

05:04.096 --> 05:06.587
I remember one day

05:06.682 --> 05:09.674
riding the Elysian Fields bus,
my father and me.

05:09.768 --> 05:11.929
We're sitting in the back behind a screen,

05:12.021 --> 05:15.434
had a sign that said "colored patrons only."

05:15.524 --> 05:16.513
Hmm.

05:17.067 --> 05:20.605
A white man we knew
named Richard Scordato,

05:21.739 --> 05:23.855
he owned an aquarium store,

05:24.950 --> 05:27.032
came back and sat with us.

05:28.120 --> 05:30.907
The driver said,

05:30.998 --> 05:35.412
"Richard, you know you can't
sit back there with them coloreds."

05:38.005 --> 05:40.496
Richard said, "They're my friends."

05:41.800 --> 05:45.509
Well, that driver
put us all off the bus that day.

05:45.596 --> 05:49.885
You see, it was a white man that did us wrong
and it was a white man that stood by us, too.

05:49.975 --> 05:52.933
And that's how it was around here back then.

06:09.578 --> 06:11.364
TONI: Mrs. Gilday?

06:11.455 --> 06:13.286
-Are you Mrs. Bernette?
-Yes, ma'am.

06:13.374 --> 06:15.114
-Come in.
-Thank you.

06:17.211 --> 06:19.122
